courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing this course, students should be able to:

1. Describe the top threats to global health: including the causes, current status, and the impact on people’s health around the world;

2. Describe the strategies that are being used, or being proposed, to mitigate the impact of the health threats

Upon completing this course, students should be able to:

1. Understand the paradigm shift of community health intervention moving beyond traditional health boundary;

2. Acquire the basic concept of setting approach for health promotion and learn how to adopt the concept for community health intervention;

3. Identify the potential settings for health promotion;

4. Select the appropriate tools for needs assessment and evaluation;

5. Acquire sufficient knowledge and skills to assist in developing community health intervention programme using the setting approach.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
1. Acquire techniques and develop tools for quantitative research, e.g. questionnaire design, choosing appropriate measures, techniques of survey interview, coding and preparation of quantitative data;
2. Conduct qualitative study, e.g. focus groups, in-depth interviews

After completing this course, students should be able to:
1. Understand the role of NGO in the society and how they complement the mainstream services;
2. Acquire the basic knowledge and skill to work in NGO.

Upon completion of the course, the students will be expected to:

1. Explain the importance of target-centred programme planning;

2. Explain why a particular group is chosen as the priority segment;

3. Identify the type of factors that affect people’s decision to change their behaviour;

4. Explain the importance of campaign positioning and how to develop a unique position;

5. Develop interventions that can facilitate behaviour change by using strategies from the marketing mix.

After completing this course, students should be able help patients with chronic diseases to:

1. Deal with problems associated their diseases from physical, psycho-social perspectives

2. Devise lifestyle programme for maintenance and improvement of health and functional well-being;
3. Learn the appropriate use of treatment, both medication and lifestyle management;
4. Communicate effectively with family, friends, and health professional;
5. Understand the role of community health practitioners in disease management

After completing this course, students should be able to:

1. Apply knowledge and skills learned from taught courses as they participate as a working member of a community organization;

2. Assist in the design, execution and/or evaluation of health promotion or health service activities of relevant health organizations.
